observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the Acting Municipal Accountant to:

submit the General Ledger, together with the Subsidiary Ledgers of the Payable accounts;

exert efforts to retrieve the details and supporting documents of the outstanding payables, and review/analyze the same to determine valid claims;

prepare the exact aging of payable accounts to identify the balances and number of years the payables have been outstanding;

prepare and send confirmation letter/s for payables with details and identified creditors/claimants, and require the immediate submission of the necessary supporting documents to facilitate payment of the accounts; otherwise,

ensure that Journal Entry Vouchers are drawn to take up the necessary adjustments on the erroneous recording/classification of the payable accounts, so that the affected accounts are correctly presented in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Review and correct all errors in the Trust Fund and General Fund books, particularly the entries involving DRRMF transactions;
Record all unrecognized assets, including equipment and infrastructure projects, and transfer these appropriately to the General Fund to facilitate depreciation and accountability;
Comply strictly with the accounting treatments prescribed in COA Circular No. 2012-002, including the year-end adjustments for trust liabilities and asset recognition;
Conduct regular reconciliations between the General Fund and Trust Fund to detect and correct discrepancies in a timely manner; and
Provide capacity-building and training for accounting staff to strengthen their understanding and application of applicable government accounting standards.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare the Fund Utilization Reports and other required documents to liquidate fund transfers from various Source Agencies;
Retrieve the documents relative to the inter-agency payables and fund transfers;
Keep subsidiary records for the recovered documents; and
After accurately establishing the unutilized balances, return them to the source agencies or the National Treasury.
We also recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to consider assigning personnel to hasten the retrieval of documents relative to the transactions and to monitor the status of the transactions.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to require the Municipal Accountant to:
Remit immediately the CY 2024 contributions amounting to ₱6,720.18 to GSIS and ₱5,745.43 to HDMF;
Perform a thorough reconciliation and review of source documents to accurately identify the unremitted inter-agency payables;
Upon completion of reconciliation, immediately remit the identified balances to the appropriate government agencies; and
Regularly reconcile the inter-agency payables to ensure timely and complete remittance of all obligations.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the concerned officials to:
Ensure strict adherence to the prescribed Perpetual Inventory Method in accounting for inventories;
Consistently prepare the Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) and weekly, submit the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and copies of the RIS to the Accounting Office to properly support the recognition of expense;
Conduct regular and complete physical counts of inventory at least twice a year;
Submit the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RCPI) to the Audit Team, Accounting Office, and the GSO within the prescribed period;
Maintain and regularly update Supplies Ledger Cards and Stock Cards for each type of supply item to ensure proper tracing and tracking of receipts and issuances of inventories;
Strengthen coordination between the General Services Office (GSO) and the Accounting Office to ensure accuracy and consistency in inventory reporting;
Provide training for key personnel on inventory management and government accounting procedures; and
Develop and enforce more stringent internal control polices for inventories, clearly defining roles, responsibilities timelines and required documentations for procurement, issuance, and reporting of supplies.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the concerned offices/personnel to:
Expedite the identification and validation of beneficiaries and proceed with the distribution of the procured items as soon as practicable;
Conduct a technical assessment of the current condition and viability of the seeds to ensure their effectiveness upon use;
Submit a written explanation from the concerned offices regarding the delay and the steps being taken to address the issue;
Ensure that in future PPAs under the LDRRMF, planning includes clear implementation schedules and early beneficiary identification to prevent similar delays; and
Establish a mechanism for regular monitoring and coordination to support the timely and efficient implementation of DRRM programs.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Gender and Development Focal Point System (GFPS) and other concerned personnel to:
Submit written justification on the inclusion of PPAs amounting to 
₱3.144 million in the GAD Accomplishment Report that were not reflected in the approved GPB and the failure to implement client-focused PPAs totaling ₱4.978 million, despite their inclusion in the GPB;
Coordinate with DILG for proper documentation and compliance regarding the changes in the approved GPB, in accordance with Item 4.1.C.7 of JMC No. 2016-01 and Item 6.2 of JMC No. 2013-01;
Reconcile the GAD Accomplishment Report (AR) with the Approved GPB to ensure consistency in reported outputs, funding, and attributions and only programs with proper GAD attribution or endorsement should be reflected in the AR; and
Enhance internal planning and monitoring mechanisms by establishing protocols for tracking implementation progress, timely reporting of deviations, and securing approvals for changes when necessary.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:

Require the Municipal Accountant to:

 Exert effort to properly identify the composition of each CIP account;

 Effect necessary adjusting entries in the books of accounts to reclassify all completed infrastructure projects still recorded under the CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts;

Compute the corresponding depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation for all completed projects as of December 31, 2023, and adjust the affected accounts;

 Closely coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to obtain the status of on-going projects to properly classify the asset accounts as of year-end.

Require the Municipal Engineer to constantly update the Municipal Accountant on the status of accomplishments of on-going agency assets and public infrastructure projects for accurate presentation of related accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive direct the Acting Municipal Accountant to:

Submit the General Ledger, together with the Subsidiary Ledgers of the Payable accounts;

Exert efforts to retrieve the details and supporting documents of the outstanding payables, and review/analyze the same to determine valid claims;

Prepare the aging of payable accounts to identify the balances and number of years the payables have been outstanding;

Prepare and send confirmation letter/s for payables with details and identified creditors/claimants, and require the immediate submission of the necessary supporting documents to facilitate payment of the accounts; otherwise,

Ensure that a Journal Voucher is drawn to take up the necessary adjustments on the erroneous recording/classification of the payable accounts, so that the affected accounts are correctly presented in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive direct the:

1. Motorpool In-charge to make sure that a pre-numbered Trip-ticket shall be issued every time the vehicle is dispatched;

2. GSO Designate to submit the Monthly Report of Official Travels and Fuel Consumption;

Acting Municipal Accountant to ensure that only those fuel expenses supported with the documentary requirement under COA Circular No.  77 – 61 are allowed and paid.

We recommended and the management agreed that:

The Inventory Committee, the GSO and the Accounting Office completes the reconciliation of all property records for accurate presentation in the Financial Statements;

Require the Inventory Committee, the GSO and the Accounting Office to reconcile all the inventory reports for proper presentation in the Financial Statements; 

Instruct the Acting Municipal Accountant to exhaust all means to retrieve the necessary data/documents to reconcile the prior years’ discrepancies and make adjustments.

We recommended and the management agreed that the Acting Municipal Accountant:

Reconcile the reciprocal accounts of all funds maintained by the Municipality, by identifying the causes of discrepancies in the corresponding subsidiary accounts and to effect immediate adjustments in the books of accounts;

Regular reconciliation of the accounts shall be made to ensure the accuracy of the reciprocal accounts;

